Create Linking Variable

The reg variable in the STATA dataset uses ISTAT region codes, which need to be mapped to NUTS2 IDs.

# Create mapping between ISTAT codes (reg) and NUTS2 IDs
region_mapping <- tibble(
  reg = c(10, 20, 30, 41, 42, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90, 100, 110, 120, 130, 140, 150, 160, 170, 180, 190, 200),
  NUTS_ID = c("ITC1", "ITC2", "ITC3", "ITH1", "ITH2", "ITH3", "ITH4", "ITH5", 
              "ITI1", "ITI2", "ITI3", "ITI4", "ITF1", "ITF2", "ITF3", "ITF5", 
              "ITF6", "ITF4", "ITG1", "ITG2", "ITC4"),
  region_name = c("Piemonte", "Valle d'Aosta/Valle d'Aoste", "Liguria", 
                  "Provincia Autonoma di Bolzano/Bozen", "Provincia Autonoma di Trento",
                  "Veneto", "Friuli-Venezia Giulia", "Emilia-Romagna", "Toscana", 
                  "Umbria", "Marche", "Lazio", "Abruzzo", "Molise", "Campania", 
                  "Basilicata", "Calabria", "Puglia", "Sicilia", "Sardegna", "Lombardia")
)

# Join regional data with mapping
regional_data_mapped <- regional_data %>%
  left_join(region_mapping, by = "reg")

# Join with shapefile
italy_map_data <- italy_nuts2 %>%
  left_join(regional_data_mapped, by = "NUTS_ID")

Note on Variable Scales and Classification

Important: The variables displayed are continuous regional averages derived from individual-level ordinal responses. While the original survey questions used ordinal scales (e.g., 0-3 or 1-4), the regional aggregation creates continuous measures.

Actual Regional Data Ranges: - Economic Adequacy: Original scale 1-4, regional averages range from ~2.58 to ~2.78 - Trust in Neighbors: Original scale 0-3, regional averages range from ~1.87 to ~2.45 - Trust in Strangers: Original scale 0-3, regional averages range from ~0.59 to ~1.07 - Walking Safety: Original scale 0-4, regional averages range from ~2.39 to ~3.17 - Neighborhood Problems: Original scale 0-3, regional averages are relatively low (~0.15 to ~0.93) - Employment Equality Attitudes: Original scale 0-3, regional averages range from ~2.61 to ~2.84

Map Classification Method: All maps use quantile classification with 5 classes, which divides the data into five groups with equal numbers of regions. This classification method maximizes the visual distinction between regions by showing the relative position of each region within the actual data distribution, rather than using the theoretical scale ranges. The legend values show the actual data ranges for each quantile.

Correlation Analysis

# Create correlation matrix
library(corrplot)

cor_data <- italy_map_data %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  select(econ_adequacy_rev, emp_labourforce, trust_general, trust_neighbour, 
         trust_stranger, rely_relatives, rely_friends, rely_neighbors,
         neighbourhood_walksafe, neigbourhood_druguser, neigbourhood_drugdealer,
         neigbourhood_vandal, empatt_equality) %>%
  na.omit()

cor_matrix <- cor(cor_data)

corrplot(cor_matrix, method = "color", type = "upper", 
         tl.col = "black", tl.srt = 45,
         addCoef.col = "black", number.cex = 0.7,
         col = colorRampPalette(c("#BB4444", "#EE9988", "#FFFFFF", "#77AADD", "#4477AA"))(200),
         title = "Correlation Matrix of Regional Indicators",
         mar = c(0,0,2,0))

Regional Rankings

# Create rankings for key indicators
rankings <- italy_map_data %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  select(NUTS_NAME, econ_adequacy_rev, emp_labourforce, trust_general) %>%
  arrange(desc(econ_adequacy_rev)) %>%
  mutate(
    econ_rank = row_number(),
    emp_rank = rank(-emp_labourforce),
    trust_rank = rank(-trust_general)
  ) %>%
  select(NUTS_NAME, econ_adequacy_rev, econ_rank, emp_labourforce, emp_rank, 
         trust_general, trust_rank)

rankings %>%
  kable(digits = 2, 
        col.names = c("Region", "Economic Adequacy", "Rank", 
                      "Employment Rate", "Rank", "General Trust", "Rank"),
        caption = "Regional Rankings by Key Indicators") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"),
                full_width = FALSE)
